Definition 3.1. Let $(\mathcal{C},\otimes)$ be a monoidal category. • A functor $F\in\mathcal{Z}_{\mathcal{\mathcal{C}}}Fun(\mathcal{C},\hbox{Vec}),$ is called a 2-trace. In particular we have natural isomorphisms $\iota_{c}(-):F(-\otimes c)\rightarrow F(c\otimes-).$ • A 2-trace $F$ is called a symmetric 2-trace (compare with the shadow structure in [PS]) if $\iota_{c}(1)=F(\mathfrak{a}_{0,1}^{1,0}).$
Definition 3.7. We say that a contravariant functor $F$ from $\mathcal{C}$ to Vec is a symmetric $2$-contratrace if $F$ is a symmetric $2$-trace on $\mathcal{C}_{op}$.
Definition 2.1. Let $M$ be a left module and a right comodule over $H$, and let $i\in\mathbb{Z}$. We say that $M\in{{}_{H}\mathcal{YD}}^{H}_{i}$ if $(h~\hskip-3.0pt{}^{{}^{\left(2\right)}}m)~\hskip-3.0pt{}_{\left<0\right>}% \otimes(h~\hskip-3.0pt{}^{{}^{\left(2\right)}}m)~\hskip-3.0pt{}_{\left<1\right% >}S^{-2i}(h~\hskip-3.0pt{}^{{}^{\left(1\right)}})=h~\hskip-3.0pt{}^{{}^{\left(% 1\right)}}m~\hskip-3.0pt{}_{\left<0\right>}\otimes h~\hskip-3.0pt{}^{{}^{\left% (2\right)}}m~\hskip-3.0pt{}_{\left<1\right>}.$ We say that $M$ is a generalized Yetter-Drinfeld module.
Definition 3.13. Let $(\mathcal{C},\otimes)$ be a monoidal category, and $\mathcal{M}$ a $\mathcal{C}$-bimodule category. Let $F\in Fun(\mathcal{M}_{op},\hbox{Vec})$ and $m\in\mathcal{M}$. The pair $(F,m)$ is called a stable central contrapair if $(F,m^{\prime})$ is a stable central pair for $\mathcal{C}_{op}$.
Definition 2.1. Let $\mathcal{C}$ be a category. A coverage $J$ on $\mathcal{C}$ is a collection $J(x)$, for each object $x$, of families of arrows $\{u_{i}\to x\mid i\in I\}$ (called covering families) with the following property: for each covering family $\{u_{i}\to x\mid i\in I\}\in J(x)$ and arrow $f\colon y\to x$ there is a covering family $\{v_{k}\to y\mid k\in K\}\in J(y)$ such that for all $k$ there is an $i\in I$ and lift as shown
Definition 4.1 Let $J:C\rightarrow D$ be a functor. A relative monad ${\bf RR}$ on $J$ or a $J$-relative monad is a collection of data of the form 1. a function $RR:Ob(C)\rightarrow Ob(D)$, 2. for each $X$ in $C$ a morphism $\eta(X):J(X)\rightarrow RR(X)$, 3. for each $X,Y$ in $C$ and $f:J(X)\rightarrow RR(Y)$ a morphism $\rho(f):RR(X)\rightarrow RR(Y)$, such that the following conditions hold: 1. for any $X\in C$, $\rho(\eta(X))=Id_{RR(X)}$, 2. for any $f:J(X)\rightarrow RR(Y)$, $\eta(X)\circ\rho(f)=f$, 3. for any $f:J(X)\rightarrow RR(Y)$, $g:J(Y)\rightarrow RR(Z)$, $\rho(f)\circ\rho(g)=\rho(f\circ\rho(g))$
Definition 5.11 Let $CC$ be a C-system. We will write $Ob$ for $Ob(CC)$ and $\widetilde{Ob}$ for $\widetilde{Ob}(CC)$. 1. Operation $T$ is defined on the set $T_{dom}=\{\Gamma,\Gamma^{\prime}\in Ob\,|\,l(\Gamma)>0\,\,and\,\,\Gamma^{% \prime}>ft(\Gamma)\}$ and takes values in $Ob$. For $(\Gamma,\Gamma^{\prime})\in T_{dom}$ one defines $T(\Gamma,\Gamma^{\prime})=p_{\Gamma}^{*}(\Gamma^{\prime})$ 2. Operation $\widetilde{T}$ is defined on the set $\widetilde{T}_{dom}=\{\Gamma\in Ob,s\in\widetilde{Ob}\,|\,l(\Gamma)>0\,\,and\,% \,\partial(s)>ft(\Gamma)\}$ and takes values in $\widetilde{Ob}$. For $(\Gamma,s)\in\widetilde{T}_{dom}$ one defines $\widetilde{T}(\Gamma,s)=p_{\Gamma}^{*}(s)$ 3. Operation $S$ is defined on the set $S_{dom}=\{r\in\widetilde{Ob},\Gamma\in Ob\,|\,\Gamma>\partial(r)\}$ and takes values in $Ob$. For $(r,\Gamma)\in S_{dom}$ one defines $S(r,\Gamma)=r^{*}(\Gamma)$ 4. Operation $\widetilde{S}$ is defined on the set $\widetilde{S}_{dom}=\{r,s\in\widetilde{Ob}\,|\,\partial(s)>\partial(r)\}$ and takes values in $\widetilde{Ob}$. For $(r,s)\in\widetilde{S}_{dom}$ one defines $S(r,s)=r^{*}(s)$ 5. Operation $\delta$ is defined on the set $\delta_{dom}=\{\Gamma\in Ob\,|\,l(\Gamma)>0\}$ and takes values in $\widetilde{Ob}$. For $\Gamma\in\delta_{dom}$ one defines $\delta(\Gamma)$ as $s_{Id_{\Gamma}}$.
Definition 3.3. We say that a complex measure $\mu$ on $G$ (i.e. an element of $C_{0}(G)^{*}$) is $c_{0}$ if $\lambda(\mu):=\int_{G}\lambda_{g}\;d\mu(g)\in L(G)$ belongs to $C^{*}_{r}(G)$. We say that a positive functional $\omega$ on $C_{0}(G)\rtimes^{f}_{\operatorname{Ad}}G$ is $c_{0}$ if for every $x\in G$, the complex measure $\mu_{x}$ defined by $\mu_{x}(F)=\omega(Fu_{x})$ for all $F\in C_{0}(G)$ is $c_{0}$ and if the function $G\rightarrow C^{*}_{r}(G):x\mapsto\lambda(\mu_{x})$ tends to zero at infinity, i.e. $\lim_{x\rightarrow\infty}\|\lambda(\mu_{x})\|=0$.
Definition 3.2 ([PV14, Definition 3.4]). Let $\mathcal{C}$ be a rigid C${}^{*}$-tensor category. $\bullet$ A cp-multiplier on $\mathcal{C}$ is a function $\varphi:\operatorname{Irr}(\mathcal{C})\rightarrow\mathbb{C}$ such that the maps $\Psi^{\varphi}_{\alpha|\beta,\alpha|\beta}$ on $(\alpha\beta,\alpha\beta)$ are completely positive for all $\alpha,\beta\in\mathcal{C}$. $\bullet$ A cp-multiplier $\varphi:\operatorname{Irr}(\mathcal{C})\rightarrow\mathbb{C}$ is said to be $c_{0}$ if the function $\varphi:\operatorname{Irr}(\mathcal{C})\rightarrow\mathbb{C}$ tends to zero at infinity. $\bullet$ A cb-multiplier on $\mathcal{C}$ is a function $\varphi:\operatorname{Irr}(\mathcal{C})\rightarrow\mathbb{C}$ such that $\|\varphi\|_{\text{\rm cb}}:=\sup_{\alpha_{i},\beta_{i}\in\mathcal{C}}\|\Psi^{% \varphi}_{\alpha_{1}|\beta_{1},\alpha_{2}|\beta_{2}}\|_{\text{\rm cb}}<\infty\;.$
Definition 3.9. A collection of categories $\mathcal{C}_{n}$ and functors $\mathcal{E}\colon\mathcal{C}_{n}\to\mathcal{C}_{n+2}\qquad\mathcal{F}\colon% \mathcal{C}_{n}\to\mathcal{C}_{n-2}$ form a categorical $\mathfrak{sl}_{2}$-action if (1) the functors $\mathcal{E}$ and $\mathcal{F}$ are biadjoint, and (2) satisfy the relations (11–12) up to isomorphism, and (3) there is an action of the nilHecke algebra on the $m$-fold composition $\mathcal{E}^{m}$.
Definition 3.2. For a constructible function $\phi$ on $X$ and a map $f\colon X\to Y$, we let $f_{!}$ be the unique linear map such that: • If $X=U\sqcup V$ with $U$ open and $V$ closed, we have $f_{!}\phi=f_{!}\phi|_{U}+f_{!}\phi|_{V}$. • If $\phi=1$ is the constant function, then $f_{!}1(y)=\chi_{c}(f^{-1}(y))$ is the compactly-supported Euler characteristic $\chi_{c}(X)=\sum_{i=0}^{\infty}(-1)^{i}\operatorname{dim}H^{i}_{c}(X)$ of the fiber over each point. The pushforward in the case where $Y=*$ is a point is sometimes called Euler integration and denoted $\int\phi\,d\chi$. Pushforward is simply performing this integration over fibers.
Definition 3.1. We call a sheaf of $k$-modules $\mathscr{F}$ on a topological space $X$ a local system if it is locally constant, i.e. if there is a finite open cover $\{U_{i}\}$, such that $\mathcal{F}|_{U_{i}}\cong k_{U_{i}}^{\oplus m}$ for some integer $m$.
