Definition 3.4.8. A quilt diagram $\mathcal{Q}\mathcal{D}=\bigl{(}\mathcal{Q},(\Sigma_{P})_{P\in\mathcal{P}_{% \mathcal{Q}}},(Y_{S})_{S\in\mathcal{S}_{\mathcal{Q}}}\bigr{)}$ in a bicategory $\mathcal{C}$ with adjoints consists of a quilt $\mathcal{Q}$ with labels in $\mathcal{C}$ as follows, and illustrated in Figure 22. • Each patch $P\in\mathcal{P}_{\mathcal{Q}}$ is labeled by an object $\Sigma_{P}\in\operatorname{Obj}_{\mathcal{C}}$. • Each oriented seam $S\in\mathcal{S}^{\rm or}_{\mathcal{Q}}$ of $\mathcal{Q}$ is labeled by a morphism $Y_{S}\in\operatorname{Mor}_{\mathcal{C}}^{1}(P^{-}_{S},P^{+}_{S})$ such that seams of opposite orientation are labeled with adjoint morphisms, i.e. $Y_{S^{-}}=(Y_{S})^{T}\in\operatorname{Mor}_{\mathcal{C}}^{1}(P^{+}_{S},P^{-}_{% S})$, since $P^{\pm}_{S^{-}}=P^{\mp}_{S}$.
Definition 3.1.2. A bicategory $\mathcal{C}$ consists of a set $\operatorname{Obj}_{\mathcal{C}}$ of objects and categories of morphisms $\operatorname{Mor}_{\mathcal{C}}(x_{1},x_{2})$ as in Definition 3.1.1 (i.e. 1-morphisms, 2-morphisms, vertical composition $\circ_{\rm v}$, and units ${\rm id}_{f}$), and for each triple $x_{1},x_{2},x_{3}\in\operatorname{Obj}_{\mathcal{C}}$ a horizontal bifunctor $\circ_{\rm h}:\bigl{(}\operatorname{Mor}_{\mathcal{C}}(x_{1},x_{2}),% \operatorname{Mor}_{\mathcal{C}}(x_{2},x_{3})\bigr{)}\to\operatorname{Mor}_{% \mathcal{C}}(x_{1},x_{3})$ consisting of • a horizontal map on 1-morphisms $\circ_{\rm h}^{1}:\operatorname{Mor}_{\mathcal{C}}^{1}(x_{1},x_{2})\times% \operatorname{Mor}_{\mathcal{C}}^{1}(x_{2},x_{3})\to\operatorname{Mor}_{% \mathcal{C}}^{1}(x_{1},x_{3}),$ • for any composable pairs $(f_{12},f_{23}),(g_{12},g_{23})$ a horizontal map on 2-morphisms $\circ_{\rm h}^{2}:\operatorname{Mor}_{\mathcal{C}}^{2}(f_{12},g_{12})\times% \operatorname{Mor}_{\mathcal{C}}^{2}(f_{23},g_{23})\to\operatorname{Mor}_{% \mathcal{C}}^{2}\bigl{(}\circ_{\rm h}(f_{12},f_{23}),\circ_{\rm h}(g_{12},g_{2% 3})\bigr{)},$ that make $\circ_{\rm h}$ into a bifunctor and horizontal composition up to 2-isomorphism, as follows: • $\circ_{\rm h}=(\circ_{\rm h}^{1},\circ_{\rm h}^{2})$ is compatible with vertical identities, i.e. $\circ_{\rm h}^{2}({\rm id}_{f_{12}},{\rm id}_{f_{23}})={\rm id}_{\circ_{\rm h}% ^{1}(f_{12},f_{23})}$, • $\circ_{\rm h}^{2}$ is associative and compatible with vertical composition, i.e. $\displaystyle\circ_{\rm h}^{2}(\circ_{\rm h}^{2}(\alpha_{12},\alpha_{23}),% \alpha_{34})$ $\displaystyle=\circ_{\rm h}^{2}(\alpha_{12},\circ_{\rm h}^{2}(\alpha_{23},% \alpha_{34})),$ $\displaystyle\circ_{\rm h}^{2}(\alpha_{12}\circ_{\rm v}\beta_{12},\alpha_{23}% \circ_{\rm v}\beta_{23})$ $\displaystyle=\circ_{\rm h}^{2}(\alpha_{12},\alpha_{23})\;\circ_{\rm v}\;\circ% _{\rm h}^{2}(\beta_{12},\beta_{23}),$ • $\circ_{\rm h}^{1}$ is associative up to 2-isom