Definition 3.3.5. A 2-functor $\mathcal{F}:\mathcal{C}\to\mathcal{D}$ between two bicategories $\mathcal{C},\mathcal{D}$ consists of • a map $\mathcal{F}:\operatorname{Obj}_{\mathcal{C}}\to\operatorname{Obj}_{\mathcal{D}}$ between the sets of objects, • functors $\mathcal{F}_{x_{1},x_{2}}:\operatorname{Mor}_{\mathcal{C}}(x_{1},x_{2})\to% \operatorname{Mor}_{\mathcal{D}}(\mathcal{F}(x_{1}),\mathcal{F}(x_{2}))$ for each $x_{1},x_{2}\in\operatorname{Obj}_{\mathcal{C}}$, which are compatible with the horizontal composition in the following sense: • $1_{\mathcal{F}(x)}\sim\mathcal{F}_{x,x}^{1}(1_{x})$ are equivalent 1-morphisms in $\mathcal{D}$ for any choice of weak units associated to $x\in\operatorname{Obj}_{\mathcal{C}}$ and $\mathcal{F}(x)\in\operatorname{Obj}_{\mathcal{D}}$. • $\mathcal{F}^{1}_{x_{1},x_{3}}(f_{12}\circ_{\rm h}f_{23})\sim\mathcal{F}^{1}_{x% _{1},x_{2}}(f_{12})\circ_{\rm h}\mathcal{F}^{1}_{x_{2},x_{3}}(f_{23})$ are equivalent 1-morphisms in $\mathcal{D}$. • For each tuple $f_{ij},g_{ij}\in\operatorname{Mor}^{1}_{\mathcal{C}}(x_{i},x_{j})$ and $\alpha_{ij}\in\operatorname{Mor}^{2}_{\mathcal{C}}(f_{ij},g_{ij})$ we have $\mathcal{F}^{2}_{x_{1},x_{3}}(\alpha_{12}\circ_{\rm h}\alpha_{23})=\mathcal{F}% ^{2}_{x_{1},x_{2}}(\alpha_{12})\circ_{\rm h}\mathcal{F}^{2}_{x_{2},x_{3}}(% \alpha_{23}).$
Definition 2.3.2. A category with Cerf decompositions is a category $\mathcal{C}$ together with • a subset $\operatorname{SMor}\subset\operatorname{Mor}_{\mathcal{C}}$ of simple morphisms, • a subset ${\rm Cerf}\subset{\rm Rel}_{\mathcal{C}}$ of local Cerf moves, which is symmetric (under exchanging the factors) and consists of pairs of composable chains of simple morphisms $f_{12},\ldots,f_{(k-1)k}\in\operatorname{SMor}$, $g_{12},\ldots,g_{(\ell-1)\ell}\in\operatorname{SMor}$ whose compositions are equal, such that • the simple morphisms generate all morphisms, i.e. for any $m\in\operatorname{Mor}_{\mathcal{C}}$ there exist $h_{12},\ldots,h_{(n-1)n}\in\operatorname{SMor}$ such that $m=h_{12}\circ\ldots\circ h_{(n-1)n}$, • the presentation in terms of simple morphisms is unique up to Cerf moves, i.e. any two presentations of the same morphism in terms of $h_{12},\ldots,h_{(n-1)n}\in\operatorname{SMor}$ and $\tilde{h}_{12},\ldots,\tilde{h}_{(\tilde{n}-1)\tilde{n}}\in\operatorname{SMor}$ are related by a finite sequence15 Throughout, we will use the term “sequence” to denote a finite totally ordered set. of identities $h_{12}\circ\ldots\circ h_{(n-1)n}=h^{\prime}_{12}\circ\ldots\circ h^{\prime}_{% (n^{\prime}-1)n^{\prime}}=\ldots=\tilde{h}_{12}\circ\ldots\circ\tilde{h}_{(% \tilde{n}-1)\tilde{n}}$ in which each equality replaces one subchain of simple morphisms by another, $\ldots\circ f_{12}\circ\ldots\circ f_{(k-1)k}\circ\ldots=\ldots\circ g_{12}% \circ\ldots\circ g_{(\ell-1)\ell}\circ\ldots$ according to a local Cerf move $\bigl{(}(f_{12},\ldots,f_{(k-1)k}),(g_{12},\ldots,g_{(\ell-1)\ell})\bigr{)}\in% {\rm Cerf}$.
Definition 3.3.2. A 2-functor $\mathcal{F}:\mathcal{C}\to\mathcal{D}$ between two 2-categories $\mathcal{C},\mathcal{D}$ consists of • a map $\mathcal{F}:\operatorname{Obj}_{\mathcal{C}}\to\operatorname{Obj}_{\mathcal{D}}$ between the sets of objects, • functors $\mathcal{F}_{x_{1},x_{2}}:\operatorname{Mor}_{\mathcal{C}}(x_{1},x_{2})\to% \operatorname{Mor}_{\mathcal{D}}(\mathcal{F}(x_{1}),\mathcal{F}(x_{2}))$ for each $x_{1},x_{2}\in\operatorname{Obj}_{\mathcal{C}}$, i.e. – maps $\mathcal{F}^{1}_{x_{1},x_{2}}:\operatorname{Mor}^{1}_{\mathcal{C}}(x_{1},x_{2}% )\to\operatorname{Mor}^{1}_{\mathcal{D}}(\mathcal{F}(x_{1}),\mathcal{F}(x_{2}))$, – maps $\mathcal{F}^{2}_{x_{1},x_{2}}:\operatorname{Mor}^{2}_{\mathcal{C}}(f_{12},g_{1% 2})\to\operatorname{Mor}^{2}_{\mathcal{D}}(\mathcal{F}^{1}_{x_{1},x_{2}}(f_{12% }),\mathcal{F}^{1}_{x_{1},x_{2}}(g_{12}))$ for each pair $f_{12},g_{12}\in\operatorname{Mor}^{1}_{\mathcal{C}}(x_{1},x_{2})$, – compatibility with identities $\mathcal{F}^{2}_{x_{1},x_{2}}({\rm id}_{f_{12}})={\rm id}_{\mathcal{F}^{1}_{x_% {1},x_{2}}(f_{12})}$, – compatibility with vertical composition, $\mathcal{F}^{2}_{x_{1},x_{2}}(f_{12}\circ_{\rm v}g_{12})=\mathcal{F}^{2}_{x_{1% },x_{2}}(f_{12})\circ_{\rm v}\mathcal{F}^{2}_{x_{1},x_{2}}(g_{12}).$ These are required to intertwine the horizontal compositions in $\mathcal{C}$ and $\mathcal{D}$ as follows: • $\mathcal{F}$ is compatible with identities, $1_{\mathcal{F}(x)}=\mathcal{F}_{x,x}^{1}(1_{x})$. • $\mathcal{F}$ is compatible with composition of 1-morphisms, i.e. for each $f_{ij}\in\operatorname{Mor}^{1}_{\mathcal{C}}(x_{i},x_{j})$ $\mathcal{F}^{1}_{x_{1},x_{3}}(f_{12}\circ_{\rm h}f_{23})=\mathcal{F}^{1}_{x_{1% },x_{2}}(f_{12})\circ_{\rm h}\mathcal{F}^{1}_{x_{2},x_{3}}(f_{23}).$ • $\mathcal{F}$ is compatible with horizontal composition of 2-morphisms, i.e. for each tuple $f_{ij},g_{ij}\in\operatorname{Mor}^{1}_{\mathcal{C}}(x_{i},x_{j})$ and $\alpha_{ij}\in\operatorname{Mor}^{2}_{\mathcal{C}}(f_{ij},g_{ij})$ $\mathcal{F}^{2}_{x_{1},x_{3}}(\alpha_{12}\circ_{\rm h}\alpha_{23})=\mathcal{F}% ^{2}_{x_{1},x_{2}}(\alpha_{12})\circ_{\rm h}\mathcal{F}^{2}_{x_{2},x_{3}}(% \alpha_{23}).$
Definition 2.2.2. The symplectic category ${\rm Symp}$ is defined as follows. • Objects are the symplectic manifolds $(M,\omega)$. • Morphisms are the equivalence classes in $\operatorname{Mor}_{{\rm Symp}}(M,N):=\operatorname{Mor}_{{\rm Symp}^{\#}}(M,N% )/\!\sim$. • Composition $[\underline{L}]\circ[\underline{L}^{\prime}]:=[\underline{L}\#\underline{L}^{% \prime}]$ is induced by the composition in ${\rm Symp}^{\#}$. Here the composition-compatible equivalence relation $\sim$ on the morphism spaces of ${\rm Symp}^{\#}$ is obtained as follows. • The subset of geometric composition moves ${\rm Comp}\subset\operatorname{Mor}_{{\rm Symp}^{\#}}\times\operatorname{Mor}_% {{\rm Symp}^{\#}}$ consists of all pairs $\bigl{(}(L_{12},L_{23}),L_{12}\circ L_{23}\bigr{)}$ and $\bigl{(}L_{12}\circ L_{23},(L_{12},L_{23})\bigr{)}$ for which the geometric composition $L_{12}\circ L_{23}$ is embedded as in (2.2.1). • The equivalence relation $\sim$ on $\operatorname{Mor}_{{\rm Symp}^{\#}}$ is defined by $\underline{L}\sim\tilde{\underline{L}}$ if there is a finite sequence of moves $\underline{L}\leadsto\underline{L}^{\prime}\leadsto\underline{L}^{\prime\prime% }\ldots\leadsto\underline{L}^{(N)}=\tilde{\underline{L}}$ in which each move replaces one subchain of simple morphisms by another, $\displaystyle\underline{L}^{(k)}=\bigl{(}\ldots,L_{ij},L_{jl},\ldots\bigr{)}$ $\displaystyle\;\leadsto\;\underline{L}^{(k+1)}=\bigl{(}\ldots,L_{ij}\circ L_{% jl},\ldots\bigr{)}$ $\displaystyle\quad\mbox{resp.}\quad\underline{L}^{(k)}=\bigl{(}\ldots,L_{ij}% \circ L_{jl},\ldots\bigr{)}$ $\displaystyle\;\leadsto\;\underline{L}^{(k+1)}=\bigl{(}\ldots,L_{ij},L_{jl},% \ldots\bigr{)}$ according to a geometric composition move $\bigl{(}(L_{ij},L_{jl}),L_{ij}\circ L_{jl}\bigr{)}\in{\rm Comp}$ resp. $\bigl{(}L_{ij}\circ L_{jl},(L_{ij},L_{jl})\bigr{)}\in{\rm Comp}$.
Definition 2.1.3. A functor $\mathcal{F}:\mathcal{C}\to\mathcal{D}$ between two categories $\mathcal{C},\mathcal{D}$ consists of • a map $\mathcal{F}:\operatorname{Obj}_{\mathcal{C}}\to\operatorname{Obj}_{\mathcal{D}}$ between the sets of objects, • for each pair $x_{1},x_{2}\in\operatorname{Obj}_{\mathcal{C}}$ a map $\mathcal{F}_{x_{1},x_{2}}:\operatorname{Mor}_{\mathcal{C}}(x_{1},x_{2})\to% \operatorname{Mor}_{\mathcal{D}}(\mathcal{F}(x_{1}),\mathcal{F}(x_{2}))$, that are compatible with identities and composition, i.e. ${\rm id}_{\mathcal{F}(x)}=\mathcal{F}_{x,x}({\rm id}_{x})\qquad\qquad\mathcal{% F}_{x_{1},x_{3}}(f_{12}\circ f_{23})=\mathcal{F}_{x_{1},x_{2}}(f_{12})\circ% \mathcal{F}_{x_{2},x_{3}}(f_{23}).$
Definition 2.1.1. A category8 Throughout, all categories are meant to be small, i.e. consist of sets of objects and morphisms. However, we will usually neglect to specify constructions in sufficient detail – e.g. require manifolds to be submanifolds of some $\mathbb{R}^{N}$ – in order to obtain sets. $\mathcal{C}$ consists of • a set $\operatorname{Obj}_{\mathcal{C}}$ of objects, • for each pair $x_{1},x_{2}\in\operatorname{Obj}_{\mathcal{C}}$ a set of morphisms $\operatorname{Mor}_{\mathcal{C}}(x_{1},x_{2})$, • for each triple $x_{1},x_{2},x_{3}\in\operatorname{Obj}_{\mathcal{C}}$ a composition map $\operatorname{Mor}_{\mathcal{C}}(x_{1},x_{2})\times\operatorname{Mor}_{% \mathcal{C}}(x_{2},x_{3})\to\operatorname{Mor}_{\mathcal{C}}(x_{1},x_{3}),% \quad(f_{12},f_{23})\mapsto f_{12}\circ f_{23},$ such that • composition is associative, i.e. we have $\bigl{(}f_{12}\circ f_{23}\bigr{)}\circ f_{34}=f_{12}\circ\bigl{(}f_{23}\circ f% _{34}\bigr{)}$ for any triple of composable morphisms $f_{12},f_{23},f_{34}$, • composition has identities, i.e. for each $x\in\operatorname{Obj}_{\mathcal{C}}$ there exists a unique9 Note that uniqueness follows immediately from the defining properties: If ${\rm id}^{\prime}_{x}$ is another identity morphism then we have ${\rm id}^{\prime}_{x}={\rm id}^{\prime}_{x}\circ{\rm id}_{x}={\rm id}_{x}$. morphism ${\rm id}_{x}\in\operatorname{Mor}_{\mathcal{C}}(x,x)$ such that ${\rm id}_{x}\circ f=f$ and $g\circ{\rm id}_{x}=g$ hold for any $f\in\operatorname{Mor}_{\mathcal{C}}(x,y)$ and $g\in\operatorname{Mor}_{\mathcal{C}}(y,x)$.
Definition 3.3.1. A (connected) d+1+1 Floer field theory is a 2-functor ${\rm Bor}_{d+1+1}\to\operatorname{Cat}$ (resp. ${\rm Bor}_{d+1+1}^{\rm conn}\to\operatorname{Cat}$) that factorizes through a symplectic 2-category and preserves adjunctions.
Definition 3.4.2. A 2-category with adjoints is a 2-category $\mathcal{C}$ as in Definition 3.1.1 together with an adjunction map $\operatorname{Mor}^{1}_{\mathcal{C}}\to\operatorname{Mor}^{1}_{\mathcal{C}},Y% \mapsto Y^{T}$ that associates to each $Y\in\operatorname{Mor}^{1}_{\mathcal{C}}(\Sigma_{0},\Sigma_{1})$ its adjoint $Y^{T}\in\operatorname{Mor}^{1}_{\mathcal{C}}(\Sigma_{1},\Sigma_{0})$ and satisfies: • Adjunction is reflexive, i.e. $(Y^{T})^{T}=Y$. • Adjoint morphisms are dual to each other in the sense that for $Y\in\operatorname{Mor}^{1}_{\mathcal{C}}(\Sigma_{0},\Sigma_{1})$ there exist $X_{Y}\in\operatorname{Mor}_{\mathcal{C}}^{2}(1_{\Sigma_{0}},Y\circ^{1}_{\rm h}% Y^{T})$ and $X_{Y}^{T}\in\operatorname{Mor}_{\mathcal{C}}^{2}(Y^{T}\circ^{1}_{\rm h}Y,1_{% \Sigma_{1}})$ satisfying identities that are illustrated in Figure 18, $\bigl{(}X_{Y}\circ^{2}_{\rm h}{\rm id}_{Y}\bigr{)}\circ_{\rm v}\bigl{(}{\rm id% }_{Y}\circ^{2}_{\rm h}X_{Y}^{T}\bigr{)}={\rm id}_{Y},\quad\bigl{(}{\rm id}_{Y^% {T}}\circ^{2}_{\rm h}X_{Y}\bigr{)}\circ_{\rm v}\bigl{(}X_{Y}^{T}\circ^{2}_{\rm h% }{\rm id}_{Y^{T}}\bigr{)}={\rm id}_{Y^{T}}.$ A bicategory with adjoints is a bicategory $\mathcal{C}$ as in Definition 3.1.2 together with an adjunction map as above, whose duality property holds for all choices of weak identity morphisms $1_{\Sigma_{0}},1_{\Sigma_{1}}$.
Definition 2.4.4. A d+1 connected Floer field theory is an adjunction preserving functor ${\rm Bor}^{\rm conn}_{d+1}\to\mathcal{C}$ to an algebraic category (such as $\mathcal{C}=\operatorname{Cat}$) that arises as composition of a functor $\mathcal{F}:{\rm Bor}^{\rm conn}_{d+1}\to\mathcal{S}$ to a symplectic category (i.e. a category such as $\mathcal{S}={\rm Symp}^{\tau}$ whose objects are symplectic manifolds) with a Yoneda-type functor arising from a 2-categorical structure on $\mathcal{S}$ that encodes Floer theory (such as the functor ${\rm Symp}^{\tau}\to\operatorname{Cat}$ constructed in Lemma 3.5.6).
Definition 3.4.9. A quilted bicategory/2-category is a bicategory/2-category $\mathcal{C}$ with adjoints in the sense of Definition 3.4.2 and with quilted composition maps29 Here and below we write a tensor product $\otimes$ to indicate a Cartesian product of sets which can be replace by a tensor product in the case of 2-morphism spaces given by Floer homology groups. $\Phi_{\mathcal{Q}\mathcal{D}}:\otimes_{e\in\mathcal{E}_{\mathcal{Q}}^{-}}% \operatorname{Mor}^{2}_{\mathcal{C}}(\underline{Y}_{e})\to\operatorname{Mor}^{% 2}_{\mathcal{C}}(\underline{Y}_{e^{+}})$ for each quilt diagram ${\mathcal{Q}\mathcal{D}}=\bigl{(}\mathcal{Q},(\Sigma_{P})_{P\in\mathcal{P}_{% \mathcal{Q}}},(Y_{S})_{S\in\mathcal{S}_{\mathcal{Q}}}\bigr{)}$ that satisfy the following: Deformation Axiom: Isomorphic quilt diagrams $\mathcal{Q}\mathcal{D}\simeq\mathcal{Q}\mathcal{D}^{\prime}$ as in Figure 24 give rise to the same quilted composition maps $\Phi_{\mathcal{Q}\mathcal{D}}=\Phi_{\mathcal{Q}\mathcal{D}^{\prime}}$. Here an isomorphism $\bigl{(}\mathcal{Q},(\Sigma_{P})_{P\in\mathcal{P}_{\mathcal{Q}}},(Y_{S})_{S\in% \mathcal{S}_{\mathcal{Q}}}\bigr{)}\simeq\bigl{(}\mathcal{Q}^{\prime},(\Sigma^{% \prime}_{P^{\prime}})_{P^{\prime}\in\mathcal{P}_{\mathcal{Q}^{\prime}}},(Y^{% \prime}_{S^{\prime}})_{S^{\prime}\in\mathcal{S}_{\mathcal{Q}^{\prime}}}\bigr{)}$ is a homeomorphism $Q_{2}\simeq Q_{2}^{\prime}$ that restricts to an orientation preserving diffeomorphism $Q_{2}{\smallsetminus}Q_{0}\simeq Q^{\prime}_{2}{\smallsetminus}Q^{\prime}_{0}$ and identifies the ends $Q_{0}\simeq Q_{0}^{\prime}$, in particular $q_{0}\simeq q_{0}^{\prime}$, and seams $Q_{1}\simeq Q_{1}^{\prime}$ in such a way that the labels $\Sigma_{P}=\Sigma^{\prime}_{P^{\prime}}$ and $Y_{S}=Y^{\prime}_{S^{\prime}}$ coincide under the induced identification of patches $\mathcal{P}_{\mathcal{Q}}\simeq\mathcal{P}_{\mathcal{Q}^{\prime}}$ and oriented seams $\mathcal{S}^{\rm or}_{\mathcal{Q}}\simeq\mathcal{S}^{\rm or}_{\mathcal{Q}^{% \prime}}$. The identity $\Phi_{\mathcal{Q}\mathcal{D}}=\Phi_{\mathcal{Q}\mathcal{D}^{\prime}}$ is with respect to the identification of ends $\mathcal{E}^{\pm}_{\mathcal{Q}}\simeq\mathcal{E}^{\pm}_{\mathcal{Q}^{\prime}}$ induced by the bijection $Q_{0}\simeq Q_{0}^{\prime}$. Cylinder Axiom: The invariant associated to a quilted cylinder as in Figure 25 – that is $Q_{2}{\smallsetminus}Q_{0}\simeq\mathbb{R}\times S^{1}$ with parallel seams $Q_{1}\simeq\mathbb{R}\times\{s_{1},\ldots,s_{N}\}$ – is the identity map on the associated cyclic morphism space. Gluing Axiom: Gluing of quilt diagrams as in Figure 26 – identifying the outgoing end of one diagram with an incoming end of another diagram – corresponds to composition of the associated quilted composition maps. Strip shrinking Axiom: Strip or annulus shrinking as in Figure 27 – removing a patch $P\simeq\mathbb{R}\times S^{1}$ or $P\simeq[0,1]\times S^{1}$ and replacing the its two adjacent seams $S,S^{\prime}$ by a single seam labeled with the composed 1-morphism $Y_{S}\circ Y_{S^{\prime}}$ (and its adjoint) – corresponds to an equality of quilted composition maps.
Definition 2.2.1. The extended symplectic category ${\rm Symp}^{\#}$ is defined as follows. • Objects are the symplectic manifolds $(M,\omega)$. • Simple morphisms $L_{12}\in\operatorname{SMor}(M_{1},M_{2})$ are the Lagrangian submanifolds $L_{12}\subset M_{1}^{-}\times M_{2}$. • General morphisms $\underline{L}=(L_{01},\ldots,L_{(k-1)k})\in\operatorname{Mor}_{{\rm Symp}^{\#}% }(M,N)$ are the composable chains of simple morphisms $L_{ij}\in\operatorname{SMor}(M_{i},M_{j})$ between symplectic manifolds $M=M_{0},M_{1},\ldots,M_{k}=N$. • Composition of morphisms $\underline{L}=(L_{01},\ldots,L_{(k-1)k})\in\operatorname{Mor}_{{\rm Symp}^{\#}% }(M,N)$ and $\underline{L}^{\prime}=(L^{\prime}_{01},\ldots,L^{\prime}_{(k^{\prime}-1)k^{% \prime}})\in\operatorname{Mor}_{{\rm Symp}^{\#}}(N,P)$ is given by algebraic concatenation $\underline{L}\#\underline{L}^{\prime}:=(L_{01},\ldots,L_{(k-1)k},L^{\prime}_{0% 1},\ldots,L^{\prime}_{(k^{\prime}-1)k^{\prime}})$. For this to form a strict category, we include trivial chains $(\;)\in\operatorname{Mor}(M,M)$ of length $k=0$ as identity morphisms.
Definition 3.1.1. A 2-category $\mathcal{C}$ is a category enriched in categories, i.e. consists of • a set $\operatorname{Obj}_{\mathcal{C}}$ of objects, • for each pair $x_{1},x_{2}\in\operatorname{Obj}_{\mathcal{C}}$ a category of morphisms $\operatorname{Mor}_{\mathcal{C}}(x_{1},x_{2})$, i.e. – a set $\operatorname{Mor}_{\mathcal{C}}^{1}(x_{1},x_{2})$ of 1-morphisms, – for each pair $f,g\in\operatorname{Mor}_{\mathcal{C}}^{1}(x_{1},x_{2})$ a set of 2-morphisms $\operatorname{Mor}_{\mathcal{C}}^{2}(f,g)$, – for each triple $f,g,h\in\operatorname{Mor}_{\mathcal{C}}^{1}(x_{1},x_{2})$ an associative vertical composition $\operatorname{Mor}_{\mathcal{C}}^{2}(f,g)\times\operatorname{Mor}_{\mathcal{C}% }^{2}(g,h)\to\operatorname{Mor}^{2}_{\mathcal{C}}(g,h),\quad(\alpha_{12},\beta% _{12})\mapsto\alpha_{12}\circ_{\rm v}\beta_{12},$ – for each $f\in\operatorname{Mor}_{\mathcal{C}}^{1}(x_{1},x_{2})$ an identity ${\rm id}_{f}\in\operatorname{Mor}_{\mathcal{C}}^{2}(f,f)$ for $\circ_{\rm v}$, • a composition functor $\operatorname{Mor}_{\mathcal{C}}(x_{1},x_{2})\times\operatorname{Mor}_{% \mathcal{C}}(x_{2},x_{3})\to\operatorname{Mor}_{\mathcal{C}}(x_{1},x_{3})$ for each triple $x_{1},x_{2},x_{3}\in\operatorname{Obj}_{\mathcal{C}}$, i.e. – an associative horizontal composition on 1-morphisms $\operatorname{Mor}_{\mathcal{C}}^{1}(x_{1},x_{2})\times\operatorname{Mor}_{% \mathcal{C}}^{1}(x_{2},x_{3})\to\operatorname{Mor}_{\mathcal{C}}^{1}(x_{1},x_{% 3}),\quad(f_{12},f_{23})\mapsto f_{12}\circ_{\rm h}f_{23},$ – for each $x\in\operatorname{Obj}_{\mathcal{C}}$ an identity $1_{x}\in\operatorname{Mor}_{\mathcal{C}}^{1}(x,x)$ for $\circ_{\rm h}$, that is $1_{x}\circ_{\rm h}f=f$ for any $f\in\operatorname{Mor}_{\mathcal{C}}^{1}(x,y)$ and $g\circ_{\rm h}1_{x}=g$ for any $g\in\operatorname{Mor}_{\mathcal{C}}^{1}(w,x)$. – for any $(f_{12},f_{23}),(g_{12},g_{23})\in\operatorname{Mor}_{\mathcal{C}}^{1}(x_{1},x% _{2})\times\operatorname{Mor}_{\mathcal{C}}^{1}(x_{2},x_{3})$ an associative horizontal composition on 2-morphisms, $\displaystyle\operatorname{Mor}_{\mathcal{C}}^{2}(f_{12},g_{12})\times% \operatorname{Mor}_{\mathcal{C}}^{2}(f_{23},g_{23})$ $\displaystyle\;\longrightarrow\;\operatorname{Mor}_{\mathcal{C}}^{2}(f_{12}% \circ_{\rm h}f_{23},g_{12}\circ_{\rm h}g_{23})$ $\displaystyle(\alpha_{12},\alpha_{23})$ $\displaystyle\;\longmapsto\;\alpha_{12}\circ_{\rm h}\alpha_{23},$ that is compatible with identities, i.e. for $f_{12}=g_{12}\in\operatorname{Mor}_{\mathcal{C}}^{1}(x_{1},x_{2})$ and $f_{23}=g_{23}\in\operatorname{Mor}_{\mathcal{C}}^{1}(x_{2},x_{3})$ we have ${\rm id}_{f_{12}}\circ_{\rm h}{\rm id}_{f_{23}}={\rm id}_{f_{12}\circ_{\rm h}f% _{23}},$ and is compatible with vertical composition, i.e. for $\alpha_{12},\beta_{12}\in\operatorname{Mor}_{\mathcal{C}}^{2}(f_{12},g_{12})$ and $\alpha_{23},\beta_{23}\in\operatorname{Mor}_{\mathcal{C}}^{2}(f_{23},g_{23})$ we have $(\alpha_{12}\circ_{\rm v}\beta_{12})\circ_{\rm h}(\alpha_{23}\circ_{\rm v}% \beta_{23})=(\alpha_{12}\circ_{\rm h}\alpha_{23})\circ_{\rm v}(\beta_{12}\circ% _{\rm h}\beta_{23}).$
Definition 3.4.6. A quilt is a tuple $\mathcal{Q}:=(q_{0},Q_{0},Q_{1},Q_{2})$ consisting of a closed oriented surface $Q_{2}$, a finite subset of points $Q_{0}\subset Q_{2}$, a 1-dimensional submanifold $Q_{1}\subset Q_{2}{\smallsetminus}Q_{0}$, and one distinguished point $q_{0}\in Q_{0}$. We moreover require $Q_{1}\subset Q_{2}{\smallsetminus}Q_{0}$ to be a closed subset with finitely many connected components, as illustrated in Figure 20. • The patches $P\in\mathcal{P}_{\mathcal{Q}}\cong\pi_{0}(Q_{2}{\smallsetminus}(Q_{0}\cup Q_{1% }))$ of $\mathcal{Q}$ are the connected components $P\subset Q{\smallsetminus}(E\cup S)$. • The seams $S\in\mathcal{S}_{\mathcal{Q}}\cong\pi_{0}(Q_{1})$ of $\mathcal{Q}$ are the connected components $S\subset Q_{1}$. The oriented seams $S\in\mathcal{S}^{\rm or}_{\mathcal{Q}}\simeq\mathcal{S}_{\mathcal{Q}}\times% \mathbb{Z}_{2}$ are pairs of seams with orientations. • For $S\in\mathcal{S}^{\rm or}_{\mathcal{Q}}$ we denote by $P^{-}_{S},P^{+}_{S}\in\mathcal{P}_{\mathcal{Q}}$ the adjacent patches whose oriented boundary contains $S^{-}$ resp. $S$ (i.e. which lie to the right resp. left of $S$), as illustrated in Figure 21. • The outgoing end of $\mathcal{Q}$ is $\mathcal{E}^{+}_{\mathcal{Q}}:=\{e^{+}\}:=\{q_{0}\}$, and the incoming ends of $\mathcal{Q}$ are the points $e\in\mathcal{E}_{\mathcal{Q}}^{-}:=Q_{0}{\smallsetminus}\{q_{0}\}$.
2.3.3 Definition. Call (mixed) cohomology theory $\mathbb{T}^{op}$ the regular theory with the list of sequents $\sqcap$1-4 over the signature $\Sigma^{op}$.
